A Turkish military convoy was targeted by a car bomb as it was moving through the outskirts of Atareb town in western Aleppo. The explosive targeted a heavy machines carrier, destroying the vehicle and killing as many as 3 people, including a Turkish soldier and a driver, and injuring another person. The convoy, previously blocked in western rural Aleppo after targeting the previous day, was moving the Iss area of southern Aleppo, along the contact lines of regime and rebel forces, in order to establish positions in the area. notes: Day 1 of clashes in Aden: Heavy fighting between Yemeni government and southern separatist forces left at least 12 combatants and 3 civilians dead in Aden on Sunday before both sides responded to calls for calm by the Saudi-led coalition. The clashes broke out in the early morning as members of the presidential guard tried to prevent thousands of supporters of the Southern Transitional Council from gathering for a rally in Khour Maksar district. The fighting between the presidential guard and southern forces spread to other areas of the district including Hadeed mountain, the government headquarters, Al Aqel roundabout and the Khour Maksar shoreline. Bin Dagher (who protesters demand be sacked) has accused the separatists of staging a coup after their fighters seized the government headquarters. Fatalities spread across 3 locations, at least one of which was controlled by separatist fighters by the end of the day.

One report indicated that regime forces may have recaptured the town. The rebel factions included Ahrar al-Sham, Nour al-Din al-Zinki Movement, Jaysh al-Ahrar, Al-Sham Corps, Army of Glory, Free Idleb Army, Jaysh al-Thani, and the Turkistan Islamic Party. Tension increased between residents of northwest Deir-ez-Zor and southern Al-Hasakeh and former Islamic State fighters after Syrian Democratic Forces released over 400 IS members of Syrian nationality, allowing them to return to their villages of origin in Deir-ez-Zor and Al-Hasakeh after weeks of detention and questioning. Several areas of Deir-ez-Zor witnessed attacks by residents on the IS members as some skirmishes took place between residents of released members. No fatalities reported. These skirmishes reportedly took place as residents reacted to the crimes previously committed by these members in their communities as well as in general retribution for the crimes IS committed when these areas were under its control. Some residents also expressed concern that these returned members intended to form IS sleeper cells upon their release.
Four bodies were found shot dead in northern Deir ez-Zor which locals accused Islamic State fighters of being responsible.

Agreement: Syrian Democratic Forces released over 400 IS members of Syrian nationality, allowing them to return to their villages of origin in Deir-ez-Zor and Al-Hasakeh after weeks of detention and questioning. Among those released are tens of commanders from Deir-ez-Zor as well as security and military officials, economists, and Shari'a officials from IS. over 120 former IS fighters joined the QSD
